<DOC><DOCNO> AP890518-0235 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-89 0241EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-18 0691</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0720</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Democratic-controlled Congress gave finalapproval to legislation raising the minimum wage for the first timein eight years, but President Bush said it was ``inevitable'' hewould kill the measure with the first veto of his administration.   The vote Wednesday was 63-37 to approve the plan, which wouldboost the minimum wage from $3.35 an hour to $4.55 by October 1991.That vote left supporters shy of the 67 needed in the Senate tooverride Bush's veto.   Majority Democrats are short of a two-thirds override margin inthe House, which passed the bill earlier this month, but sponsorshave promised a veto override attempt nonetheless.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. trade deficit, benefiting from recordexport sales, shrank dramatically to $8.86 billion in March, thegovernment said in a report that prompted some economists toquestion their earlier assessment that the country's tradeimprovement had stalled out.   The Commerce Department said Wednesday the March deficit wasdown 9.8 percent from February's imbalance of $9.82 billion, afigure that was revised from an initial deficit of $10.5 billion.</TEXT><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Florida officials have accused the penny stockbrokerage Blinder, Robinson and Co. of a variety of securities lawviolations and moved to kick the firm out of the state.   Comptroller Gerald Lewis said Wednesday the state named 29former and current employees in a civil action to revoke theirlicenses, including company President Meyer Blinder and his son,vice president Larry Blinder.   Denver-based Blinder, which has offices in 37 states _ including10 in Florida _ and the District of Columbia was ordered toimmediately stop violating Florida securities laws.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Miffed at what it called an ``hysterical'' and``irresponsible'' rejection of its $2.1 billion takeover bid, AmwayCorp. withdrew its offer to acquire rival Avon Products Inc.   The move came late Wednesday, just hours after Avon's boardrejected Amway's $39-a-share offer saying that uniting the nation'stwo biggest companies in person-to-person sales would cause aculture clash with disastrous consequences.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   American Telephone andamp; Telegraph Co. said it wouldcut certain long-distance prices by about $140 million to complywith a new federal regulatory plan.   The price cuts announced Wednesday will take effect on July 1,the same time the Federal Communications Commission's new price-capplan begins. Under the price-cap plan adopted March 16, the FCClimits the prices ATandamp;T charges rather than the profits it makes.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Consumer Reports says the Ford Bronco II liftstwo wheels off the ground during accident-avoidance maneuvers, andthe magazine's June issue recommends that buyers avoid thesport-utility car.   The magazine rated the Bronco II ``poor'' in emergency handlingbut said it was more stable than the Suzuki Samurai, anotherJeep-style car that Consumer Reports labeled ``not acceptable''last June.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   McGraw-Hill Inc. stock tumbled after the companyannounced a standstill agreement barring British publisher RobertMaxwell from attempting to take over the company for 15 years.   The pact with Maxwell Communications Corp. was part of a jointeducational publishing venture announced Wednesday between Maxwellaffiliate Macmillan Inc. and McGraw-Hill.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The heads of the four largest U.S. commodityfutures exchanges, which have come under federal investigation,have told the Senate they oppose additional legislation regulatingtheir industry.   ``We recognize that in recent months some have questioned ourintegrity and expressed doubt about our ability to police ourmarkets,'' Karsten Mahlmann, chairman of the Chicago Board ofTrade, said Wednesday.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   The stock market overcame some ambivalence over the latest newson the trade deficit to post a moderate gain in brisk tradingWednesday. The Dow Jones industrials average rose 8.98 to 2,462.43,recouping most of Tuesday's 10.44-point setback.   The dollar rose to its highest point since 1987 against theJapanese yen and since 1986 against the West German mark. Bondprices were mixed.   Precious metals futures were down sharply; grain and soybeanfutures closed mostly lower, energy prices were down, and livestockprices were down as meat prices rallied.</TEXT></DOC>